Exploring Bay Wheels Rides Data¶

by RAJAT PRASAD¶

Bay Wheels is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California operated by Motivate in a partnership with the Metropolitan Transportation Commission and the Bay Area Air Quality Management District. Bay Wheels is the first regional and large-scale bicycle sharing system deployed in California and on the West Coast of the United States. It was established as Bay Area Bike Share in August 2013. As of January 2018, the Bay Wheels system had over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. On June 28, 2017, the system officially re-launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company. After Motivate's acquisition by Lyft, the system was subsequently renamed to Bay Wheels in June 2019.

The bicycles are available 24 hours a day, seven days a week for periods ranging from a single ride (up to 30 minutes) to a day pass, in 30-minute increments, or customers can purchase an annual subscription which gives them unlimited rides up to 45-minutes in duration. Single rides cost 2 dollar per trip, day passes cost 10 dollar per day, and memberships cost 15 dollar per month or 149 dollar per year.

For more about Bay Wheels.

About Dataset¶

For this project I am using Bay Wheels dataset. The dataset contains information about 2,506,983 bicycle rides from January to December for year 2019. A summary of all variables avilable in dataset can be seen below.

Variable Name Variable Discription
bike_id Unique id of each bicycle.
bike_share_for_all_trip A reduced pricing option for users who qualify for CalFresh, the SFMTA Lifeline pass or PG&E CARE discount.
duration_sec Trip Duration in seconds.
end_station_id Unique id of station at where trip ends.
end_station_latitude Latitude of end station.
end_station_longitude Longitude of end station.
end_station_name Name of station where trip end.
end_time End time of trip.
rental_access_method How bicycle ride is access either through app or clipper.
start_station_id Unique id of station from where trip start.
start_station_latitude Latitude of start station.
start_station_longitude Longitude of start station.
start_station_name Name of station where trip start.
start_time Start time of trip.
user_type Whether the rider is subscriber or customer.

For more about Bay Wheels Dataset.

Task¶

This project is divided into two major parts. This is the first part of the project in which I perform an exploratory data analysis on a bay wheels dataset for year 2019.

In [2]:
file_path = pathlib.Path("bay-wheels-dataset/bay_wheels_combined.csv")

if file_path.exists():
    # check if final combined dataset is avaliable, then read that dataset
    bike_df = pd.read_csv('bay-wheels-dataset/bay_wheels_combined.csv', low_memory=False)

else:
    # combining all datasets into one dataset
    os.chdir('bay-wheels-dataset')
    datasets = [dataset for dataset in glob.glob('*.{}'.format('csv'))]
    bay_wheels = pd.concat([pd.read_csv(data, low_memory=False, header=0) for data in datasets], sort=True)
    bay_wheels.to_csv("bay_wheels_combined.csv", index=False, encoding='utf-8-sig')
    os.chdir('/')

Documenting Issuses¶

  • Dropping un-neccessary columns like 'start_station_id', 'end_station_id', 'rental_access_method'.
  • Removing null values from dataset.
  • Changing data type of 'start_time' and 'end_time' to datetime.
  • Changing data type of 'bike_id' to str.
  • Changing data type of 'user_type' and 'bike_share_for_all_trip' to category.
  • Separating date, hour, day, month from start_time and end_time columns.
  • Converting ride duration from second to minute.
  • Creating new column for bike ride distance.
  • Sorting bike rides by start time.

# function to find the distance of each ride
# I take reference from geeks of geeks

from math import radians, cos, sin, asin, sqrt 

def dist_btwn_station(start_station,end_station):
    lat1, lon1 = start_station
    lat2, lon2 = end_station
    
    # radius of earth
    radius = 6371
    
    lat = radians(lat2 - lat1)
    lon = radians(lon2 - lon1)
    
    a = (sin(lat / 2)**2 + cos(radians(lat1)) * cos(radians(lat2)) * sin(lon / 2)**2)
    
    c = 2 * asin(sqrt(a))
    
    distance = radius * c
    
    return distance

bay_df['distance_km'] = bay_df.apply(lambda x: dist_btwn_station((x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude']), (x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude'])), axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The final dataset has 2262979 rows and 22 columns.

Columns I dropped:

Column Name Column Description Reason
end_station_id Unique id of station at where trip ends. Does not contribute in analysis.
start_station_id Unique id of station at where trip starts. Does not contribute in analysis.
rental_access_method How bicycle ride is access either through app or clipper. Contains too many null values about 2386145.

Columns I added:

Column Name Column Description
start_date Start date of ride.
start_month Start month of ride.
start_day Start day of ride.
start_hour Start time of ride.
end_date End date of ride.
end_month End month of ride.
end_day End day of ride.
end_hour End time of ride.
duration_min Ride duration in minute.
distance_km Ride distance in kilometre.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main features of interest is bike rides and how it is related to other fetures like user_type, bike_share_for_all. I am also interested rides distance and duration over week days and months.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • duration_min
  • duration_km
  • start_hour
  • start_month
  • start_day
  • user_type
  • bike_share_for_all

# setting background style
sns.set_style('darkgrid')

# setting figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))

ax = plt.subplot(111)

# plotting bar chart
ax = sns.countplot(data = bay_wheels, x='user_type', palette=['indigo','deeppink'], ax=ax)

# total number of rows
total = bay_wheels.shape[0]


for i in ax.patches:
    # get_x for left or right and get_height for up or down
    ax.text(i.get_x()+.26, i.get_height()-150000, \
            str(round((i.get_height()/total)*100, 2))+'%', fontsize=25, color='white')

    
plt.xlabel('User Type', fontsize=15, weight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Number of Rides', fontsize=15, weight='bold')
plt.xticks(fontsize=13)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.title('Bike Rides by User Type', fontsize=18, weight='bold');

Observation

  • About 82.23% of rides are done by subscriber of Bay Wheels bicycle sharing system and about 17.77% of rides are done by users who are not subscriber of bicycle sharing system.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • About 82.23% of total rides are done by subscriber of Bay Wheels and only 17.77% of rides done by customer.
  • About 92.25% of rides where users don't have price reduction option and only 7.85% of rides where users have CalFresh, SFMTA's Lifeline pass or PG&E's CARE discount.
  • Most of the rides are of duration 10 to 15 minutes for distance 1 to 2 km.
  • Most of rides are done on regular days specially 8 in the morning and at 5 in the evening.
  • Most of the rides starts from Market St at 10th St and Berry St at 4th St.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, I did perform transformation on ride duration. It is in second I convert it into minute for easily interpretation.

I have to modify the range of ride duration and distance to clearly visualize the distribution because most of the rides are under 10 to 15 minute and 1 to 2 kilometers.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Customer ride more for longer duration and distance than subscriber.
  • More rides are done by subscriber over days of weeks or months.
  • People ride for longer duration and distance on weekends than regular days.
  • People ride for longer distance in morning than evening.
  • Subscriber take more ride than customer over weeks or month.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • start_hour and end_hour are highly correlated.
  • Average ride duration and distance for customer is more than subscriber.
  • Average ride duration and distance is less for users who got discount than user who did not get discount.
